In article <strnlghtCB5I07.BB9@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>Not necessarily. If they can read traffic now from, say, terrorists that use
>what they think is an unbreakable system but isn't, and if the terrorists
>got hold of the Skipjack algorithm and programmed it without key escrow to
>get a really secure system, that wuld definitely be detrimental to national
>security, politics aside.

I doubt terrorists would ever use Clipper.  They can already use 
triple DES which has an equivalent keyspace greater than Skipjack,
and use RSA (illegally) for key exchange.

Key-Escrow is about enforcing laws concerning victimless crimes
(drug dealing, pornography, thought-crime, etc.)

-Thomas


